'''Discovery Family''' is an American [[pay television]] channel owned by [[Discovery, Inc.]] with a minority ownership held by [[Hasbro]].

The network was first launched on October 7, 1996 as '''Discovery Kids Channel''', a spin-off of [[Discovery Channel]] that featured science, nature and adventure-themed programs aimed towards children ages 6-11. In April 2009, Hasbro announced a [[joint venture]] with Discovery, Inc. to relaunch Discovery Kids as '''The Hub''' (later '''Hub Network''') on October 10, 2010; Hasbro handled programming while Discovery handled distribution and advertising sales. The Hub was intended to be a general, youth-oriented network with a "diverse" lineup, primarily featuring programming adapted from Hasbro franchises (such as ''[[Transformers]]'', its [[Parker Brothers|board game]]s, ''[[My Little Pony]]'', ''[[Pound Puppies]]'' and ''[[Littlest Pet Shop]]'') along with other family-oriented programs such as sitcom reruns and films.

On September 25, 2014, following reports earlier in the year that Hub Network president [[Margaret Loesch]] would step down by the end of the year, Discovery acquired 10% of Hasbro's stake in the network, and replaced Loesch with Henry Schleiff, who leads sister networks such as [[Destination America]] and [[Investigation Discovery]]. On October 13, 2014, Hub Network was re-branded as Discovery Family to which Hasbro remains a minority partner and programs the network's daytime lineup with children's programs carried over from Hub Network, while its prime-time lineup was replaced with reruns of [[non-fiction]] programs from Discovery Channel's library, including [[popular science|science]] and nature programs.

As of February 2015, approximately 69,513,000 American households (59.7% of households with television) receive Discovery Family.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2015/02/22/list-of-how-many-homes-each-cable-network-is-in-as-of-february-2015/366230/|title=List of how many homes each cable network is in as of February 2015|last=Seidman|first=Robert|work=TV by the Numbers|publisher=Zap2it|date=February 22, 2015|accessdate=March 14, 2015}}</ref>

==History==
===As Discovery Kids Channel/Discovery Kids (1996–2010)===
[[Discovery Inc.|Discovery Communications]] launched Discovery Kids Channel on October 7, 1996, as part of a suite of four new [[digital cable]] channels that included [[Destination America|Discovery Travel & Living]], [[Discovery Civilization]], and [[Science Channel]].<ref name=blueskies>{{cite book|last=Parsons|first=Patrick|title=Blue Skies: A History of Cable Television|date=2008|work=Temple University Press|location=Philadelphia|isbn=1592137067}}<!--|accessdate=September 23, 2014--></ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Digital Play in the U.S. of A|url=http://realscreen.com/1999/04/01/25107-19990401/3/|last=Kirchdoerffer|first=Ed|accessdate=September 23, 2014|work=Realscreen|date=April 1, 1999}}</ref> Upon its launch, the network primarily offered adventure, nature, and science-themed programs aimed towards a children's audience between ages 6 and 11.<ref name="NBC Discovery">{{cite web|title=Discovery Gets NBC Kids' Block|url=http://www.multichannel.com/news/orphan-articles/discovery-gets-nbc-kids-block/154693|last=Umstead|first=Thomas|work=Multichannel News|accessdate=September 23, 2014|date=December 7, 2001}}</ref> Marjorie Kaplan, the network's senior vice president, explained that the creation of Discovery Kids was influenced primarily by kids who were watching its [[Discovery Channel|parent network]]'s programming together with their parents.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2003/tv/news/adults-discovery-kiddie-programs-1117880923/|title=Adults 'Discovery' kiddie programs|last=Oei|first=Lily|work=Variety|date=February 23, 2003|accessdate=September 24, 2014}}</ref> From 1996 until 2000, Discovery Kids was carried by only a select few cable television providers. By late 2001, the channel was carried in at least 15 million homes.<ref name="NBC Discovery"/> In September 2001, a [[Discovery Kids (Canada)|Canadian version]] of Discovery Kids was launched in partnership with [[Corus Entertainment]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Discovery Kids Launches With a Unique Blend of "Edu-tainment"|url=http://www.corusent.com/home/Corporate/PressReleases/tabid/1697/Default.aspx?Id=34|work=Corus Entertainment|accessdate=September 23, 2014|date=August 8, 2001}}</ref>

In December 2001, Discovery Kids announced a partnership with [[NBC]], in which it would produce a new Saturday morning block for the network known as ''[[Discovery Kids on NBC]]'', beginning in September 2002. The block, which replaced [[TNBC|a teen-oriented block consisting only of sitcoms]], featured programming that met the [[U.S. Federal Communications Commission]]'s (FCC) [[E/I|educational programming guidelines]], including new original series (such as the [[reality television]] series ''[[Endurance (TV series)|Endurance]]''), existing Discovery Kids programming, along with children's spin-offs of programs from sister networks, such as [[Animal Planet]] and Discovery Channel.<ref>{{cite web|title=Discovery Kids sets NBC sked|url=https://variety.com/2002/tv/news/discovery-kids-sets-nbc-sked-1117864789/|last=Oei|first=Lily|work=Variety|accessdate=September 23, 2014|date=April 2, 2002}}</ref>

With the launch of the new block, Discovery Kids also branched out into animated programming with the premieres of ''[[Kenny the Shark]]'' and ''[[Tutenstein]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Kids mixed on new skeds|url=https://variety.com/2003/tv/news/kids-mixed-on-new-skeds-1117895265/|last=Oei|first=Lily|last2=McClintock|first2=Pamela|work=Variety|accessdate=September 23, 2014|date=November 6, 2003}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Nets face back to school blues|url=https://variety.com/2003/tv/news/nets-face-back-to-school-blues-1117891278/|last=Oei|first=Lily|work=Variety|accessdate=September 23, 2014|date=August 24, 2003}}</ref> In March 2006, Discovery declined to renew its contract with NBC for its Saturday morning block, citing a desire to focus exclusively on the Discovery Kids cable channel. Since the launch of the NBC block, Discovery Kids had grown its cable carriage to over 43 million homes.<ref>{{cite web|title=Discovery Kids parts with NBC|url=https://variety.com/2006/tv/news/discovery-kids-parts-with-nbc-1117940034/|last=Riddell|first=Robert|work=Variety|accessdate=September 23, 2014|date=March 19, 2006}}</ref> NBC would replace the Discovery Kids block with [[Qubo]] in September 2006.<ref>{{cite web|last=Hampp|first=Andrew|title=NBC Debuts Kids Programming Brand Qubo|url=http://adage.com/article/media/nbc-debuts-kids-programming-brand-qubo/111473/|accessdate=February 14, 2014|work=Ad Age|date=August 24, 2006}}</ref>

===As The Hub/Hub Network (2010–2014)===
[[File:Hub Network logo 2014.png|thumb|125px|left|Hub Network's last logo used until October 12, 2014]]
On April 30, 2009, toy manufacturer and multimedia company [[Hasbro]] announced that it would be forming a [[joint venture]] with Discovery Communications to relaunch Discovery Kids as a new family-oriented television channel. Under the arrangement, Discovery would be in charge of handling advertising sales and distribution for the new channel while Hasbro would be involved in acquiring and producing programming. While the network planned to maintain educational series (including those carried over from Discovery Kids), plans called for new original programs based off Hasbro-owned franchises such as ''[[G.I. Joe]]'', ''My Little Pony'', ''[[Transformers (toy line)|Transformers]]'' and [[game show]]s adapted from its board game brands.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/entertainmentnewsbuzz/2010/01/discovery-and-hasbro-name-new-kids-channel-the-hub.html|title=Discovery and Hasbro Name New Kids Channel "The Hub"|last=Flint|first=Joe|work=Los Angeles Times|date=January 14, 2010|accessdate=September 23, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1118003029.html?categoryId=14&cs=1|title=Hasbro Nabs Discovery Kids Stake|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120630141400/http://www.variety.com/article/VR1118003029?refCatId=14|archivedate=June 30, 2012|last=Schneider|first=Michael|date=April 30, 2009|work=Variety|accessdate=July 12, 2017|deadurl=yes|df=}}</ref>

In January 2010, Discovery and Hasbro announced that the new network would be known as '''The Hub'''; two months later, the companies announced that The Hub would be launched on October 10, 2010. The network planned to continue targeting Discovery Kids' main demographic of children aged 2-14 (a market which staff felt was being abandoned by its competitors such as [[Nickelodeon]] and [[Disney Channel]] in favor of [[tween (demographic)|tweens]]) but also planned to feature a prime-time block with family-oriented programming. Veteran television executive and the network's president and [[chief executive officer]] [[Margaret Loesch]] stated that The Hub's goal was to be "vibrant" and "diverse" in its programming and that the channel would not purely be a marketing vehicle for Hasbro products.<ref name="owens1">{{cite news|url=http://www.post-gazette.com/pg/10283/1091189-67.stm|last=Owens|first=Rob|title=Tuned In: The Hub Network Offers Programs for Younger Children|date=October 10, 2010|accessdate=October 10, 2010|work=[[Pittsburgh Post-Gazette]]|quote=The Hub (Formerly Discovery Kids) Launches at 10:00AM Today.}}</ref> The network's original imaging was developed by Troika Design Group and built around an emblem nicknamed the "hubble" – which was designed to embody a "catalyst of action and imagination". The final logo design was the result of a number of drafts by Troika designers, some of which had incorporated typography similar to Hasbro's logo.<ref name="nyt-hubreboot">{{cite news|title=A Children’s Channel Retools|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/10/11/business/media/11adco.html?_r=0|accessdate=October 13, 2014|work=The New York Times|date=October 10, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=The Hub Logo – Case Study|url=http://www.troika.tv/hub-logo-case-study/|publisher=Troika Design Group|accessdate=October 13, 2014}}</ref>

To promote the launch of The Hub, sneak previews of shows slated to air on the channel such as ''[[Cosmic Quantum Ray]]'', ''[[The Twisted Whiskers Show]]'' and ''[[Family Game Night (TV series)|Family Game Night]]'' aired on [[Science Channel]], [[Animal Planet]] and [[TLC (TV network)|TLC]] respectively.<ref>https://animesuperhero.com/forums/threads/the-hubs-schedule-for-10-10-10-11-men-in-black-the-series-is-coming.5037321/page-2</ref> The Hub was finally launched on its launching date October 10, 2010, with ''The Twisted Whiskers Show'' being the first program to air followed by an episode of ''[[Dennis the Menace and Gnasher (2009 TV series)|Dennis and Gnasher]]'' and ''Cosmic Quantum Ray''.<ref name="owens1"/><ref name="boston-launch">{{cite news|url=http://www.boston.com/business/articles/2010/10/07/hasbro_joins_crowded_market_with_new_childrens_channel|title=From Toys to TV: Hasbro Joins Crowded Market with New Children's Channel|last=Steinberg|first=Brian|work=[[Boston Globe]]|date=October 7, 2010|accessdate=October 10, 2010}}</ref> The Hub's launch programming would include the game show ''[[Family Game Night (TV series)|Family Game Night]]'', animated television series ''[[Pound Puppies (2010 TV series)|Pound Puppies]]'', ''[[My Little Pony: Friendship Is Magic]]'' – a new animated entry in the ''My Little Pony'' franchise developed by [[Lauren Faust]] and ''[[Deltora Quest (anime)| Deltora Quest]]'' alongside reruns of the [[Jim Henson]] series ''[[Fraggle Rock]]'' and the preschool-oriented programs ''[[Animal Mechanicals]]'' and ''[[The WotWots]]''.<ref name=launch>{{cite web|url=http://www.broadcastingcable.com/article/450819-Discovery_Hasbro_Aim_for_Perfect_10s.php|title=Discovery, Hasbro Aim for Perfect 10s|last=Atkinson|first=Claire|work=Broadcasting & Cable|date=March 29, 2010|accessdate=September 23, 2014}}</ref><ref name="owens1"/><ref name="boston-launch"/>

In a June 2011 debt filing with the [[U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission|Securities and Exchange Commission]], Discovery Communications indicated that the channel may be worth less than previously believed, based on low viewership figures. The management of The Hub subsequently underwent a fair value analysis of the channel. A Discovery Communications spokesperson considered the action to be "a [[pro-forma]] accounting exercise", and noted that Discovery felt "very positive, and encouraged by The Hub's early days' performance, and ability to grow its audience in the future."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.deadline.com/2011/06/is-the-hub-due-for-a-writedown-discovery-debt-filing-raises-that-possibility|title=Is THE HUB Due For A Writedown? Discovery Debt Filing Raises That Possibility|last=Lieberman|first=David|work=Deadline Hollywood|date=June 13, 2011|accessdate=September 23, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.benzinga.com/markets/bonds/11/06/1168097/less-than-meets-the-eye-is-the-hub-in-trouble|title=Less Than Meets The Eye: Is The Hub In Trouble?|last=Chen|first=Jonathan|work=Benzinga|date=June 14, 2011|accessdate=September 23, 2014}}</ref>

In March 2013, The Hub picked up its first work from [[POW! Entertainment]], ''[[Stan Lee's Mighty 7]]'', an animated pilot film to be aired in early 2014. The network also began to phase in an amended branding as the '''Hub Network'''.<ref name=tfc>{{cite web|url=http://www.thefutoncritic.com/news/2013/03/20/the-hub-network-unveils-2013-14-program-slate-with-six-new-additions-to-join-nine-returning-original-series-307012/20130320hub01|title=The Hub Network Unveils 2013-'14 Program Slate with Six New Additions to Join Nine Returning Original Series|work=The Futon Critic|date=March 20, 2013|accessdate=March 21, 2013}}</ref> In late 2013, Hub Network introduced an updated logo, and a new imaging campaign, "Making Family Fun", which was developed by the Los Angeles-based agency Oishii Creative.<ref>{{cite web|title=All in the Brand: Making Family Fun|url=http://www.oishiicreative.com/project/hub-network-rebrand/|publisher=Oishii Creative|accessdate=October 13, 2014}}</ref>

===As Discovery Family (2014–present)===
On June 12, 2014, it was reported that Margaret Loesch would step down from her role as Hub Network president and CEO by the end of the year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.deadline.com/2014/06/hub-president-ceo-margaret-loesch-to-exit/|title=HUB President & CEO Margaret Loesch To Exit|last=Adreeva|first=Nellie|work=Deadline Hollywood|date=June 12, 2014|accessdate=June 13, 2014}}</ref> On September 17, 2014, ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]'' reported that Discovery Communications was preparing to acquire a controlling stake in Hub Network from Hasbro and then retool it as '''Discovery Family'''. Along with Discovery's CFO Andrew Warren, Hasbro staff acknowledged that increasing competition in the children's media landscape – especially by subscription video-on-demand services such as [[Netflix]] – had an effect on the overall performance of the network and Hasbro's original content.<ref name="Discovery Family"/><ref name="modify"/><ref name="adweek-df"/> As it was majority-owned by a competitor, other major toy companies such as [[Mattel]] refused to purchase advertising time on Hub Network, affecting its ability to air advertising that targeted its main audience; by 2014, the network had made only $9 million per year. Discovery staff was also unable to display a full commitment to Hub Network's operation, due to factors such as the troubled launch of the [[Oprah Winfrey Network (U.S. TV channel)|Oprah Winfrey Network]]. Believing that they had overvalued its stake in the venture, Hasbro decided to cede the operation of the network to Discovery so it could focus more on content and its core toy business.<ref name="adweek-df">{{cite web|url=http://www.adweek.com/news/television/after-rocky-few-years-hasbro-s-tv-strategy-changing-again-163083|title=The Rise and Fall and Rise of Hasbro's TV Strategy|last=Thielman|first=Sam|work=Adweek|date=February 23, 2015|accessdate=February 23, 2015}}</ref>

Discovery and Hasbro publicly announced the planned re-branding on September 25, 2014, Hasbro's CEO [[Brian Goldner]] explained that Discovery Family would be the "next chapter" in its joint venture with Discovery, "[combining] highly rated award-winning storytelling around Hasbro's brands and Discovery's most popular non-fiction shows that appeal to both children and families alike." Hub Network was re-launched as Discovery Family on October 13, 2014 – just over four years since the original launch of The Hub. With these changes, Discovery Communications now holds a 60% stake in the joint venture; Hasbro continues to hold a 40% stake in Discovery Family, and continues to program the network's daytime lineup with children's programming. Following the re-launch, the network's primetime lineup was replaced by reruns of family-oriented factual programming from Discovery Channel's library.<ref name="Hub to Discovery">{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/hub-rebrand-as-discovery-family-735656|title=The Hub to Rebrand as Discovery Family Channel as Discovery Takes Control|last=Szalai|first=Georg|work=The Hollywood Reporter|date=September 25, 2014|accessdate=September 25, 2014}}</ref> Henry Schleiff, who leads sister networks such as Destination America and Investigation Discovery, leads the re-launched network, with Tom Cosgrove (who previously served as CEO of Discovery Channel and [[Science (TV network)|Science]]) as general manager.<ref name="Hub to Discovery"/>

In re-launching Hub Network, Discovery executives noted that there would be a larger emphasis on programming of interest to both children and their parents; Warren argued that since [[Freeform (TV channel)|ABC Family]] had become, in his opinion, aimed towards teenage girls, there was a gap in the broadcasting industry for a new, family-oriented network.<ref name="Discovery Family">{{cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/discovery-to-take-control-of-the-hub-network-1410979842|title=Discovery to Take Control of Hub Children's Network|last=Flint|first=Joe|last2=Hagey|first2=Keach|last3=Ziobro|first3=Paul|work=The Wall Street Journal|date=September 17, 2014|accessdate=September 17, 2014}}</ref><ref name="modify">{{cite web|url=http://www.multichannel.com/news/news-articles/discovery-hasbro-modify-hub-partnership/383946|title=Discovery, Hasbro Modify Hub Partnership|last=Farrell|first=Mike|work=MultiChannel News|date=September 17, 2014|accessdate=September 17, 2014}}</ref> With these shifts in the network's operation, it was announced on October 7, 2014 that ''[[Transformers: Robots in Disguise (2015 TV series)|Transformers: Robots in Disguise]]'' – a sequel to ''Transformers: Prime'' that had been scheduled to premiere on Hub Network, would instead air on [[Cartoon Network]].<ref name="variety-tfmoveback">{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2014/tv/news/hasbro-transformers-robots-in-disguise-cartoon-network-1201322969/|title=Hasbro's 'Transformers' Return to Original TV Home, Cartoon Network|last=Graser|first=Marc|work=Variety|date=October 7, 2014|accessdate=October 12, 2014}}</ref> Hasbro Studios president Stephen Davis felt that Cartoon Network was a more appropriate home for a ''Transformers'' series due to its male-oriented demographics,<ref name="adweek-df"/> describing Hub Network's lineup as being "traditionally skewed towards girls".<ref name="variety-tfmoveback"/>  Other recent ''Transformers'' [[List of Transformers TV series|animated series]] preceding the original launch of The Hub also aired on Cartoon Network.<ref name="deadline-tfmoved"/><ref name="variety-tfmoveback"/> Davis remarked that Hasbro was still "100% committed" to its joint venture with Discovery.<ref name="deadline-tfmoved">{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2014/10/transformers-robots-in-disguise-series-move-cartoon-network-hasbro-847192/|title=Hasbro Moves New 'Transformers' Series To Cartoon Network|last=Andreeva|first=Nellie|work=Deadline Hollywood|date=October 7, 2014|accessdate=October 7, 2014}}</ref> Despite the move for ''Robots in Disguise'', fellow Hub Network ''Transformers'' series ''[[Transformers: Rescue Bots]]'' would remain on Discovery Family for its third season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2014/10/22/discovery-family-channel-to-premiere-the-third-season-of-transformers-rescue-bots-november-1/318247/|title=Discovery Family Channel to Premiere the Third Season of ''Transformers Rescue Bots'' November 1|last=Kondolojy|first=Amanda|work=TV by the Numbers|date=October 22, 2014|accessdate=October 24, 2014|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141025193437/http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2014/10/22/discovery-family-channel-to-premiere-the-third-season-of-transformers-rescue-bots-november-1/318247/|archivedate=October 25, 2014|df=}}</ref>

==Programming==
{{further|List of programs broadcast by Discovery Family}}
[[File:2950hollywoodway.JPG|thumb|right|Hasbro Studios ([[Burbank, California]] headquarters pictured) supplies much of the network's programming.]]
The majority of Discovery Family's daytime programs are animated and live-action series tied to [[media franchise]]s owned by Hasbro itself, with newer series produced through the [[Hasbro Studios]] division, such as ''Pound Puppies'' and ''Transformers: Rescue Bots''. As the Hub Network, it also previously aired [[game show]]s tied to Hasbro's [[board game]]s, such as ''Family Game Night''. Following the relaunch as Discovery Family, the remainder of its lineup was replaced with family-oriented science and nature-related programs from its sister network [[Discovery Channel]] such as ''[[Africa (TV series)|Africa]]'', ''[[Extreme Engineering|Extreme Engineering: Big Reveals]]'', ''[[Flying Wild Alaska]]'' and ''[[Time Warp (TV series)|Time Warp]]''.<ref name="Hub to Discovery"/>

One of the network's most noteworthy series has been ''My Little Pony: Friendship Is Magic'', an animated series developed and first produced by Lauren Faust which is associated with the recent reboot of Hasbro's ''My Little Pony'' franchise. The series not only became The Hub's highest-rated program within its target demographic of young girls, but attracted an unexpectedly significant [[cult following]] [[My Little Pony: Friendship Is Magic fandom|among male teens and adults]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tvguide.com/news/bronies-my-little-pony-friendship-magic-1068692.aspx|title=Give Bronies a Break! In Defense of Adult My Little Pony Fans|last=Gennis|first=Sadie|work=TV Guide|date=July 31, 2013|accessdate=September 23, 2014}}</ref> 

The network has also acquired new series unrelated to Hasbro properties, including ''[[The Aquabats! Super Show!]]'', ''[[Dan Vs.]]'', ''[[Majors & Minors]]'', ''[[The Haunting Hour: The Series|R. L. Stine's The Haunting Hour]]'' and ''[[SheZow]]'', while four of its programs, ''[[Strawberry Shortcake's Berry Bitty Adventures]]'', ''The Twisted Whiskers Show'', ''[[Maryoku Yummy]]'' and ''[[Care Bears: Welcome to Care-a-Lot]]'', came from properties of [[American Greetings]].<!-- Note that both AG and Hasbro are licensing partners to each other. How should we notify readers of that? -->

During its years as the Hub Network, the channel also aired reruns of other outside series, such as ''Fraggle Rock'' and ''[[Lois & Clark: The New Adventures of Superman]]'', a collection of various [[Warner Bros. Animation]] series, such as ''[[Batman Beyond]]'', ''[[Batman: The Animated Series]]'', ''[[Superman: The Animated Series]]'', ''[[Animaniacs]]'', and ''[[Tiny Toon Adventures]]'', a few former [[Fox Kids]] shows such as ''[[Goosebumps (TV series)|Goosebumps]]'' and ''[[Ninja Turtles: The Next Mutation]]'', and various off-network sitcoms (at the end of the Hub Network's run, these included ''[[Blossom (TV series)|Blossom]]'', ''[[Step by Step (TV series)|Step by Step]]'' and ''[[Sister, Sister (TV series)|Sister, Sister]]''); ''Blossom'', the only sitcom on Discovery Family's schedule, returned for a time in 2016. A limited amount of original Discovery Kids programming, such as ''[[Adventure Camp]]'' and ''[[Flight 29 Down]]'', remained on the lineup upon its launch as The Hub.<ref name="modify"/>

==Availability==
Discovery Family operates one feed nationally, and does not operate a [[Timeshift channel|timeshift feed]] for the [[West Coast of the United States|west coast]].<ref name="nyt-hubreboot"/> A [[1080i]] [[high-definition television|high-definition]] simulcast of the network was introduced alongside its re-launch as The Hub, with [[Dish Network]], [[Verizon FiOS]], and [[AT&T U-verse]] as the first to carry the HD feed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hd-report.com/2010/10/11/verizon-launches-the-hub-hd-on-fios-tv|title=Verizon launches The Hub HD on FiOS TV|work=HD Report|date=October 11, 2010|accessdate=September 23, 2014}}</ref>

===International versions===
On March 31, 2016, the pan-[[EMEA]] version of [[Discovery World (TV channel)|Discovery World]] was re-launched, as a regional version of Discovery Family.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://worldscreen.com/tvmiddleeastafrica/discovery-family-comes-to-south-africa-on-dstv/|title=Discovery Family Comes to South Africa on DStv|last=Brzoznowski|first=Kristin|work=WorldScreen|date=March 24, 2016|accessdate=April 21, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://nextvame.com/discovery-networks-multichoice-launch-discovery-family/|title=Discovery Networks and Multiple Choice to Launch Discovery Family|last=Tirvengadum|first=Priscilla|work=NexTV News|date=March 25, 2016|accessdate=July 8, 2016}}</ref>

On September 14, 2017, a [[French language|French]] version was launched in [[France]].

