{{Infobox software | name = Workflowy | logo = Workflowy Logo.jpg | logo alt = Workflowy logo | logo caption = Workflowy logo (June 2018) | screenshot = <!-- Image name is enough. --> | screenshot alt = | caption = | developer = WorkFlowy, Inc. | released = August 2, 2010 | operating_system = [[iOS]], [[Android (operating system)|Android]], [[Web application|Web]] | genre = [[Productivity software]] | alexa = {{Increase}} 11,662 ({{as of|2018|06|7|alt=June 2018}})<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.alexa.com/siteinfo/workflowy.com|title= workflowy.com Site Infosite|publisher=[[Alexa Internet]]|accessdate=7 June 2018}}</ref> | website = {{URL|https://workflowy.com}} }}
'''Workflowy''' is a simple [[Web application|web-based]] [[outliner]] created by Mike Turitzin and Jesse Patel at a [[Y Combinator (company)|Y Combinator]] startup camp. The idea for Workflowy arose from Patel’s prior work experience in [[project management]] and his frustration with the lack of useful tools.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.slate.com/articles/technology/technology/2012/08/workflowy_the_note_taking_app_that_changed_the_way_i_organize_my_life_.html | title=Everything Is a List | work=Slate | date=August 2, 2012 | accessdate=April 25, 2016 | author=Manjoo, Farhad}}</ref>
The app operates on a [[freemium]] business model and its straightforward list-like interface has been described as "uncluttered."<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.pcworld.com/article/2038607/5-free-tools-to-organize-your-thoughts.html | title=5 free Web tools to organize your thoughts | work=PC World | date=September 30, 2013 | accessdate=April 25, 2016 | author=Zukerman, Erez}}</ref> by ''PC World'' in 2013 and "minimalistically elegant" by ''The Atlantic'' in 2016.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.theatlantic.com/notes/2016/01/tech-tips-for-the-new-year-cloudmagic-workflowy-low-light-filter-on-ipad/422853/ | title=Tech Tips for the New Year: CloudMagic, Workflowy, ‘Low Light’ Filter on iPad | work=The Atlantic | date=January 6, 2016 | accessdate=November 22, 2016 | author=Fallows, James}}</ref> Since its launch Workflowy has developed what the ''Geek Wire'' describe as "a cult-like following." <ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.geekwire.com/2018/workflowly-founder-new-list-update-popular-app-keeping-purists-happy/ | title=At top of WorkFlowy founder’s to-do list: Keeping his app’s cult-like following happy | work=Geek Wire | date=May 5, 2018 | accessdate=May 18, 2018 | author=Lystra, Tony}}</ref>
